Two colour forms from Parsley Bay, Vaucluse, Sydney Harbour, NSW, Australia. September 1982. Showing the typical oral tentacles at the front of the head, on either side of the mouth and the smaller rhinophores just above the eyes. At the back you can see the large parapodial flaps which have a black edge. These parapodia enclose the mantle cavity in which the fragile plate-like shell is found. In the lower photo, part of a black ring can be seen. This outlines the hole (foramen) which leads to the cavity in which the shell is found. PHOTO: Bill Rudman.
